</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="lectotypification">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Lectotypification.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
We have selected the Michaux collection from Knoxville, Tennessee at P as lectotype of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliolatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Convolvulus ciliolatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as it appears to be the only extant specimen that fits the protologue.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Very variable particularly in the leaf shape (entire to deeply lobed) and in the relative and absolute sizes of the sepals as also in the size of the corolla and leaves, although the leaves are usually small (c. 5 cm long).</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Distinguished by the white corolla with a pink throat and the prominently veined sepals. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="candicans">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea candicans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a form in which the abaxial leaf surface is white-tomentellous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
